A ``walking stick'' is two logs bolted or otherwise secured together with two or three planks firmly attached on top
that serves as a floating walking and working surface and that is used in the loading of logs onto vessels from the water.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
</FOOTNOTE>

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) They shall be planked and be no less than 24 inches 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(60.9 cm) wide; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) They shall extend along the entire length of all rafts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on the offshore side of the vessel, and to the means of access to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the log raft(s); and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) They shall be buoyant enough to keep the walking 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
surface above the waterline when employees are walking on them. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart E_Opening and Closing Hatches 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.41 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Coaming clearances. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Weather deck.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 If a deck load (such as lumber or other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
smooth sided deck cargo) over 5 feet (1.5 m) high is stowed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
within 3 feet (.91 m) of the hatch coaming and employees handling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
hatch beams and hatch covers are not protected by a coaming at 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
least 24-inch (.61 m) high, a taut handline shall be provided 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
along the side of the deckload. The requirements of &sect;1918.35 are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
not intended to apply in this situation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Intermediate deck.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) There shall be a 3 foot (.91 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
m) working space between the stowed cargo and the coaming at both 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
sides and at one end of the hatches with athwartship hatch beams, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and at both ends of those hatches with fore and aft hatch beams, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
before intermediate deck hatch covers and hatch beams are removed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or replaced by employees. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The 3 foot (.91 m) clearance required by paragraph 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)(1) of this section is not required on the covered portion of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a partially open hatch, nor is it required when lower decks have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
been filled to hatch beam height with cargo of such a nature as 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
to provide a safe surface upon which employees may work. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) For purposes of paragraph (b)(1) of this section, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fitted gratings which are in good condition shall be considered a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
part of the decking when properly placed within the 3 foot (.91 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
m) area. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) Grab rails or taut handlines shall be provided for the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
protection of employees handling hatch beams and hatch covers, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
when bulkheads, lockers, reefer compartments or large spare parts 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are within 3 feet (.91 m) of the coaming. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) This section does not apply to hatches which are opened 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
or closed by hydraulic or other mechanical means. However, in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
all cases in which the 3 foot (.91 m) clearance does not exist, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
means shall be taken to prevent stowed cargo which is likely to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shift from falling into the hold. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.42 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Hatch beam and pontoon bridles. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) Hatch beam and pontoon bridles shall be: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) long enough to easily reach the holes, rings, or other 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
lifting attachments on the hatch beams and pontoons; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) of adequate strength to safely lift the load; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) properly maintained, including covering or blunting of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
protruding ends in wire rope splices. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) Bridles for lifting hatch beams shall be equipped with 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
toggles, shackles, or hooks, or other devices of such design that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
they cannot become accidentally dislodged from the hatch beams 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
with which they are used. Hooks other than those herein 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
described may be used only when they are hooked into the standing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
part of the bridle. Toggles, when used, shall be at least 1 inch 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2.5 cm) longer than twice the longest diameter of the holes into 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
which they are placed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) Bridles used for lifting pontoons and plugs shall have 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the number of legs required by the design of the pontoon or plug, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and all legs shall be used. Where any use of a bridle requires 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
fewer than the number of legs provided, idle legs shall be hung 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
on the hook or ring, or otherwise prevented from swinging free. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
