<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(c)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Lifelines.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When employees are working on log booms or cribs, lifelines shall be furnished and hung overside to the water's edge.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Jacob's ladder.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When a log boom is being worked, a Jacob's ladder meeting the requirements of &sect;1918.22 shall be provided for each
gang working alongside unless other safe means of access are provided. However, no more than two Jacob's ladders are
required for any single log boom being worked. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Life-ring.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When working a log boom alongside a ship, a U.S. Coast Guard approved 30 inch (76.2 cm) life-ring, with no less than 90
feet (27.4 m) of line shall be provided either on the floating unit itself or aboard the ship in the immediate vicinity
of each floating unit being worked. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Rescue boat.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 When employees are working on rafts or booms, a rescue boat shall be immediately available. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.89 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Hazardous cargo. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(See also &sect;1918.2(j).) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(a)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Employer preparations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Before cargo handling operations begin, the employer shall ascertain whether any hazardous cargo is to be handled
and shall determine the nature of the hazard. The employer shall inform employees of the nature of the hazard and any
special procedures to be taken to prevent employee exposure, and shall instruct employees to stay clear of and to notify
supervision of any leaks or spills. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Handling hazardous cargo.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Hazardous cargo shall be slung and secured so that neither the draft nor individual packages can fall as a result of
tipping the draft or slacking of the supporting gear. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Emergency procedures.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 If hazardous cargo is spilled or its packaging leaks, employees shall be removed from the affected area until the employer
has ascertained the specific hazards; has provided any equipment, clothing and ventilation, and fire protection
equipment necessary to eliminate or protect against the hazards; and has instructed cleanup employees in a safe method
of cleaning up and disposing of a spill and disposing of leaking containers. Actual cleanup or disposal work shall
be conducted under the supervision of a designated person. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->
Subpart I_General Working Conditions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.90 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Hazard communication. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(See &sect;1918.1(b)(6).) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.91 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Housekeeping. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 General.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Active work areas shall be kept free of equipment and materials not in use, and clear of debris, projecting nails, strapping
and other sharp objects not necessary to the work in progress. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Slippery surfaces.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The employer shall eliminate conditions causing slippery walking and working surfaces in immediate areas used by
employees. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Free movement of drafts.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Dunnage shall not be placed at any location where it interferes with the free movement of drafts. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Dunnage height.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Dunnage racked against sweat battens or bulkheads shall not be used when the levels of such racks are above the safe
reach of employees. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Coaming clearance.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Dunnage, hatch beams, tarpaulins or gear not in use shall be stowed no closer than 3 feet (.91 m) to the port and starboard
sides of the weather deck hatch coaming. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Nails.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 (1) Nails which are protruding from shoring or fencing in the immediate work areas shall be rendered harmless. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Dunnage, lumber, or shoring material in which there are visibly protruding nails shall be removed from the immediate
work area, or, if left in the area, the nails shall be rendered harmless. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Ice aloft.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Employees shall be protected from ice which may fall from aloft. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;1918.92 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Illumination. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Walking and working areas.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Walking, working, and climbing areas shall be illuminated. Unless conditions described in the regulations of the
U.S. Coast Guard (33 CFR 154.570) exist in the case of specific operations, illumination for cargo transfer operations
shall be of an average minimum light intensity of 5-foot-candles (54 lux). Where occasional work tasks require more
light than that which is consistently and permanently provided, supplemental lighting shall be used. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Intensity measurement.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The lighting intensity shall be measured at the task/working surface, in the plane in which the task/working surface
is present. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
