<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
2. In the case of derrick systems, the test load shall be lifted with the ship's normal tackle with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
derrick at the minimum angle to the horizontal for which the derrick system was designed (generally 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
15 degrees), or at such greater angle as may be agreed. The angle at which the test was made 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
should be stated in the certificate 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.1. The SWL shown is applicable to swinging derrick systems only. When derricks are used in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
union purchase, the SWL (U) is to be shown on Form 2 (U). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.2. In the case of heavy derricks, care should be taken to ensure that the appropriate stays are 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
correctly rigged. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3. In the case of cranes, the test load is to be hoisted, slewed and luffed at slow speed. Gantry and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
traveling cranes together with their trolleys, where appropriate, are to be traversed and travelled 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
over the full length of their track. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.1. In the case of variable load-radius cranes, the tests are generally to be carried out with the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
appropriate test load at maximum, minimum and intermediate radii. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.2. In the case of hydraulic cranes where limitations of pressure make it impossible to lift a test 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
load 25 percent in excess of the safe working load, it will be sufficient to lift the greatest 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
possible load, but in general this should not be less than 10 percent in excess of the safe 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
working load. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4. As a general rule, tests should carried out using test loads, and no exception should be allowed in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
the case of initial tests. In the case of repairs/replacement or when the periodic examination calls 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
for re-test, consideration may be given to the use of spring or hydraulic balances provided the SWL 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
of the lifting appliance does not exceed 15 tones. Where a spring or hydraulic balance is used, it 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
shall be calibrated and accurate to within 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=1 -->
#
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
2 percent and the indicator should remain constant for 5 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
minutes. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1. If the test weights are not used, this is to be indicated in Col. (3). 
